Use `Window` lifecycle events — save in `OnStopped` and restore in `OnResumed`. Here's the recommended approach:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass:**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped, so save here too
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

### Key things to know

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| `OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch | Initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated` only |
| Android back button skips `Stopped` | Save in **both** `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying` |
| Keep handlers fast (<2s) | Android ANR timeout is ~5s; iOS has similar limits |
| `Deactivated` ≠ `Stopped` | A notification shade triggers `Deactivated` without backgrounding — don't save there |

`Preferences` is ideal here since draft text is a small string. For larger state, use file serialization instead.
